From Rabbi Joshua Davidson Temple Emanu-el NYC My two sons were bar mitzvahed at this Temple... Dear Friends, Just as we were gathering for worship in our sanctuary this morning, a gunman entered the Tree of Life Congregation in Squirrel Hill, reportedly declared

his hatred of Jews, and killed multiple congregants. Our hearts reach out to the families of those murdered and wounded and to their synagogue community. When we enter a house of worship we do so believing it a place of safety, spiritually and physically. While our security

procedures are always attuned to potential threats, though we ourselves have received none, we will of course remain vigilant, increasing our security presence in light of this attack. And in the coming days we will learn how we as a sister congregation might respond to offer

comfort to those suffering through this terrible tragedy. In this time of fear in our nation, we turn to the words of our prayer book: “Fervently we invoke Your blessing upon our country, O God. Guard us from calamity and injury; may we face adversity with courage and resolve.

And may peace and good-will unite all the people of our land…blessing our nation with a renewed strength of spirit.” May we, through our efforts individually and collectively, realize this hope. In sorrow, Rabbi Joshua M. Davidson
